{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Du9ApF17u4ZP3DQpSeHWLG","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t{\n2\t  \"layout\": \"data_figure\",\n3\t  \"content\": {\n4\t    \"title\": \"NB00: sphingolipid biosynthesis is constitutive across the rescue strain series\",\n5\t    \"figure\": \"figures/00_sphingolipid_locus_heatmap.png\",\n6\t    \"caption\": \"Sphingolipid locus log2(CPM+1) heatmap (WT, \\u0394fur \\u0394sspb, intermediate, rescued); pathway is constitutive \\u2014 neither induced nor suppressed \\u2014 ruling out Fur-driven sphingolipid biosynthesis upregulation.\",\n7\t    \"data_source\": \"REPORT.md \\u00a7Phase A; notebooks/00_orientation.ipynb cell 6\"\n8\t  },\n9\t  \"speaker_notes\": \"Before formal hypothesis testing began, the NB00 orientation notebook established a critical reframing. This heatmap shows the sphingolipid biosynthesis gene locus in log2(CPM+1) across all four strains in the series: wild type (4580), the \\u0394fur \\u0394sspb background (4584), the intermediate strain (4659), and the fully rescued \\u0394lpxc strain (4672). The picture is flat to slightly decreasing \\u2014 not induced.\\n\\nThis eliminated the simplest version of the Fur story: 'Fur normally represses sphingolipid biosynthesis, so \\u0394fur derepresses it, giving the cell extra CPG to substitute for lipid A.' That mechanism would predict the sphingolipid locus going UP in 4584 and UP further in 4672. The data show the opposite \\u2014 the pathway is constitutive. The CPG pool is already standing in wild type; rescue is not a matter of making more sphingolipid in response to lipid A loss.\\n\\nThis observation redirected the analysis. The question became not 'why does \\u0394fur induce sphingolipid biosynthesis?' but 'given that the CPG pool is already present, what Fur-released components enable its trafficking into the outer membrane?' That question frames Layer 1 \\u2014 and the fitness data answer it: the Fur-released TonB-dependent transporters and iron-uptake systems (Path A) carry the envelope-stress fitness signal, plausibly because they are the transport machinery enabling CPG routing to the outer membrane via the shared Lpt apparatus (Uchendu 2026 bioRxiv).\\n\\nCaveat: this orientation figure uses CPM normalization from NB00 and is descriptive rather than statistically DE-tested. The formal characterization of sphingolipid biosynthesis constitutivity with FDR-corrected statistics \\u2014 spt logFC -0.64 FDR 0.002, sphk -0.40 FDR 0.02, zero of six biosynthesis genes significantly UP \\u2014 belongs to NB04 in Layer 3. What the speaker highlights here is the conceptual reframing the figure motivates, not the statistical support that comes later in S3. The delivery note: 'NB00 showed us the sphingolipid pool is already there; the question Layer 1 answers is how Fur derepression routes it.'\\n\\nTransition: with this orientation established \\u2014 Fur derepresses transport, not sphingolipid biosynthesis \\u2014 we turn to the fitness data to ask which part of the Fur regulon actually carries phenotypic weight under envelope stress.\",\n10\t  \"id\": 7,\n11\t  \"substory_id\": \"S1\",\n12\t  \"position\": 7\n13\t}\n14\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e40dfb86-d98a-440c-9600-9fae013cc371","uuid":"b9f4b6cc-f975-46c8-9748-678604924bf6","timestamp":"2026-06-07T16:37:34.304Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/aparkin/BERIL-research-observatory/projects/caulobacter_fur_lipida_loss/talks/draft_1/audit/revisions/F004.slide.json","content":"{\n  \"layout\": \"data_figure\",\n  \"content\": {\n    \"title\": \"NB00: sphingolipid biosynthesis is constitutive across the rescue strain series\",\n    \"figure\": \"figures/00_sphingolipid_locus_heatmap.png\",\n    \"caption\": \"Sphingolipid locus log2(CPM+1) heatmap (WT, \\u0394fur \\u0394sspb, intermediate, rescued); pathway is constitutive \\u2014 neither induced nor suppressed \\u2014 ruling out Fur-driven sphingolipid biosynthesis upregulation.\",\n    \"data_source\": \"REPORT.md \\u00a7Phase A; notebooks/00_orientation.ipynb cell 6\"\n  },\n  \"speaker_notes\": \"Before formal hypothesis testing began, the NB00 orientation notebook established a critical reframing. This heatmap shows the sphingolipid biosynthesis gene locus in log2(CPM+1) across all four strains in the series: wild type (4580), the \\u0394fur \\u0394sspb background (4584), the intermediate strain (4659), and the fully rescued \\u0394lpxc strain (4672). The picture is flat to slightly decreasing \\u2014 not induced.\\n\\nThis eliminated the simplest version of the Fur story: 'Fur normally represses sphingolipid biosynthesis, so \\u0394fur derepresses it, giving the cell extra CPG to substitute for lipid A.' That mechanism would predict the sphingolipid locus going UP in 4584 and UP further in 4672. The data show the opposite \\u2014 the pathway is constitutive. The CPG pool is already standing in wild type; rescue is not a matter of making more sphingolipid in response to lipid A loss.\\n\\nThis observation redirected the analysis. The question became not 'why does \\u0394fur induce sphingolipid biosynthesis?' but 'given that the CPG pool is already present, what Fur-released components enable its trafficking into the outer membrane?' That question frames Layer 1 \\u2014 and the fitness data answer it: the Fur-released TonB-dependent transporters and iron-uptake systems (Path A) carry the envelope-stress fitness signal, plausibly because they are the transport machinery enabling CPG routing to the outer membrane via the shared Lpt apparatus (Uchendu 2026 bioRxiv).\\n\\nCaveat: this orientation figure uses CPM normalization from NB00 and is descriptive rather than statistically DE-tested. The formal characterization of sphingolipid biosynthesis constitutivity with FDR-corrected statistics \\u2014 spt logFC -0.64 FDR 0.002, sphk -0.40 FDR 0.02, zero of six biosynthesis genes significantly UP \\u2014 belongs to NB04 in Layer 3. What the speaker highlights here is the conceptual reframing the figure motivates, not the statistical support that comes later in S3. The delivery note: 'NB00 showed us the sphingolipid pool is already there; the question Layer 1 answers is how Fur derepression routes it.'\\n\\nTransition: with this orientation established \\u2014 Fur derepresses transport, not sphingolipid biosynthesis \\u2014 we turn to the fitness data to ask which part of the Fur regulon actually carries phenotypic weight under envelope stress.\",\n  \"id\": 7,\n  \"substory_id\": \"S1\",\n  \"position\": 7\n}\n","numLines":14,"startLine":1,"totalLines":14}}}
