{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01RavGLJD5iUrcUmFWsro8vq","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_017xVYxwUNks9T4m8sJBprK4","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/home/aparkin/BERIL-research-observatory/projects/caulobacter_fur_lipida_loss/talks/draft_1/audit/revisions/F004.revised_slide.json","content":"{\n  \"id\": 7,\n  \"position\": 7,\n  \"substory_id\": \"S1\",\n  \"layout\": \"data_figure\",\n  \"content\": {\n    \"title\": \"NB00: sphingolipid biosynthesis is constitutive across the rescue strain series\",\n    \"figure\": \"figures/00_sphingolipid_locus_heatmap.png\",\n    \"caption\": \"Sphingolipid locus log2(CPM+1) heatmap (WT, Δfur Δsspb, intermediate, rescued); pathway is flat across strains in NB00 orientation (CPM-descriptive, not DE-tested). FDR-tested formal verdict on slide 16: 0/6 UP; spt −0.64 FDR 0.002.\",\n    \"data_source\": \"REPORT.md §Phase A; notebooks/00_orientation.ipynb cell 6\"\n  },\n  \"speaker_notes_seed\": \"Before formal hypothesis testing began, the NB00 orientation notebook established a critical reframing. This heatmap shows the sphingolipid biosynthesis gene locus in log2(CPM+1) across all four strains: wild type (4580), the Δfur Δsspb background (4584), the intermediate strain (4659), and the fully rescued Δlpxc strain (4672). The picture is flat to slightly decreasing — not induced.\\n\\nSpeaker caveat (load-bearing): this CPM heatmap from NB00 is orientation-level and descriptive only. It does not license a 'ruling out' claim by itself. The formal statistical ruling-out lives in NB04, presented on slide 16: 0/6 biosynthesis genes UP at FDR<0.05; spt logFC −0.64 FDR 0.002; sphk −0.40 FDR 0.02. Delivery note: 'NB00 showed us the sphingolipid pool looks flat even at a CPM-level look — biosynthesis is not going up in the rescue strains. Slide 16 gives you the formal numbers. What this pattern tells us is that the question Layer 1 must answer is about routing, not synthesis.'\\n\\nThis observation redirected the analysis: not 'why does Δfur induce sphingolipid biosynthesis?' but 'given that the CPG pool is already present in WT, what Fur-released components enable its trafficking into the outer membrane?' That question frames Layer 1 — and the fitness data answer it: the Fur-released TonB-dependent transporters (Path A) carry the envelope-stress fitness signal, plausibly because they are the transport machinery enabling CPG routing via the shared Lpt apparatus.\\n\\nTransition: with this orientation established — Fur derepresses transport, not sphingolipid biosynthesis — we turn to the fitness data to ask which part of the Fur regulon actually carries phenotypic weight under envelope stress.\",\n  \"evidence_anchors\": [\n    {\"kind\": \"report_section\", \"ref\": \"REPORT.md §Phase A NB00\"},\n    {\"kind\": \"report_section\", \"ref\": \"REPORT.md §Finding 4 table (sphingolipid biosynthesis constitutive; 0/6 UP; spt −0.64 FDR 0.002)\"}\n  ],\n  \"revision_log\": [\n    {\n      \"revised_at\": \"2026-06-07T00:00:00Z\",\n      \"finding_id\": \"F004\",\n      \"finding_class\": \"claim_evidence\",\n      \"summary\": \"Caption 'ruling out Fur-driven sphingolipid biosynthesis upregulation' removed — a CPM-normalised orientation figure cannot license a rule-out claim; replaced with CPM-descriptive qualifier ('flat across strains in NB00 orientation; CPM-descriptive, not DE-tested') plus forward pointer to FDR-tested slide 16 verdict (0/6 UP; spt −0.64 FDR 0.002). Speaker notes restructured to surface the caveat as a load-bearing delivery instruction, explicitly distinguishing the NB00 orientation-level visual from the NB04 statistical evidence.\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9528,"cache_read_input_tokens":27820,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tok