sphk −0.40 FDR 0.02. If an audience member asks 'does this figure prove the biosynthesis pathway isn't induced?' — the honest answer is: 'No; the CPM heatmap shows it looks flat, but slide 16 gives you the FDR-corrected numbers that license the formal claim.'\\n\\nDelivery note: 'NB00 showed us the sphingolipid pool looks flat even at this CPM-level view — biosynthesis isn't going up in the rescue strains. Slide 16 gives the formal numbers. What this pattern tells us is that the question Layer 1 must answer is about routing, not synthesis.'\\n\\nThis observation redirected the analysis: not 'why does Δfur induce sphingolipid biosynthesis?' but 'given that the CPG pool is already present in WT, what Fur-released components enable its trafficking into the outer membrane?' That question frames Layer 1 — the Fur-released TonB-dependent transporters (Path A) carry the envelope-stress fitness signal, plausibly enabling CPG routing via the shared Lpt apparatus (Uchendu 2026 bioRxiv).\\n\\nTransition: with this orientation established — Fur derepresses transport, not sphingolipid biosynthesis — we turn to the fitness data to ask which part of the Fur regulon carries phenotypic weight under envelope stress.\",\n  \"evidence_anchors\": [\n    {\"kind\": \"report_section\", \"ref\": \"REPORT.md §Phase A NB00\"},\n    {\"kind\": \"report_section\", \"ref\": \"REPORT.md §Finding 4 table (sphingolipid biosynthesis constitutive; 0/6 UP; spt −0.64 FDR 0.002)\"}\n  ],\n  \"revision_log\": [\n    {\n      \"revised_at\": \"2026-06-07T00:00:00Z\",\n      \"finding_id\": \"F004\",\n      \"finding_class\": \"claim_evidence\",\n      \"summary\": \"Caption 'ruling out Fur-driven sphingolipid biosynthesis upregulation' removed — a CPM-normalised orientation figure cannot license a rule-out claim; replaced with CPM-descriptive qualifier ('flat across strains in NB00 orientation; CPM-descriptive, not DE-tested') plus forward pointer to FDR-tested slide 16 verdict (0/6 UP; spt −0.64 FDR 0.002). Speaker notes restructured to surface the caveat as a load-bearing delivery instruction, explicitly distinguishing the NB00 orientation-level visual from the NB04 statistical evidence on slide 16.\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n","structuredPatch":[{"oldStart":1,"oldLines":28,"newStart":1,"newLines":25,"lines":[" {","-  \"id\": null,","-  \"position\": 29,","-  \"substory_id\": \"S6\",","+  \"id\": 7,","+  \"position\": 7,","+  \"substory_id\": \"S1\",","   \"layout\": \"data_figure\",","   \"content\": {","-    \"title\": \"Four-panel master figure maps all five adaptive layers onto a single envelope cross-section\",","-    \"figure\": \"figures/NB07_synthesis_master.png\",","-    \"caption\": \"Layer 1 (Fur-released transport relief), Layer 2 (ChvI two-phase cascade), Layer 3 (constitutive sphingolipid substitution), Layer 4 (PG remodeling + Pal-Tol induction), and Layer 5 (comparative route unavailability) — integrated across the *Caulobacter* Δ*lpxC* envelope. Recommended Figure 1 (REPORT.md §Key Findings; NB07_synthesis.ipynb cell 2).\",","-    \"data_source\": \"REPORT.md §Key Findings line 5; notebooks/07_synthesis.ipynb cell 2\"","+    \"title\": \"NB00: sphingolipid biosynthesis is constitutive across the rescue strain series\",","+    \"figure\": \"figures/00_sphingolipid_locus_heatmap.png\",","+    \"caption\": \"Sphingolipid locus log2(CPM+1) heatmap (WT, Δfur Δsspb, intermediate, rescued); pathway is flat across strains in NB00 orientation (CPM-descriptive, not DE-tested). FDR-tested formal verdict on slide 16: 0/6 UP; spt −0.64 FDR 0.002.\",","+    \"data_source\": \"REPORT.md §Phase A; notebooks/00_orientation.ipynb cell 6\"","   },","-  \"speaker_notes_seed\": \"This slide exists because the throughline promised it — and slides 27 and 28 both name it explicitly — but the deck was delivering only a scorecard table in its place. The 4-panel NB07_synthesis_master.png is the integrative payoff: the one image that places all five adaptive layers into a single spatial frame of the Caulobacter outer-membrane cross-section. Walk the audience through each panel before advancing to the scorecard. Panel A and B show the envelope cross-section with the five-layer overlay: Fur-released TBDTs repositioning outer-membrane import capacity (Layer 1); ChvI temporal scheduling with early regulators and late structural genes (Layer 2); the constitutive CPG sphingolipid pool, pre-positioned in the outer leaflet by maintained Lpt machinery, occupying the space vacated by lipid A (Layer 3); downshifted PG biosynthesis with Pal-Tol specifically upregulated for retrograde phospholipid homeostasis (Layer 4). Panels C and D overlay the fitness and transcript data to show the quantitative support under each layer. The comparative Layer 5 (spt 7,0,0,0; ChvI 6,0,0,0 by NCBI) explains why this integrated program is Caulobacter-specific. The phrase 'partially independent' is architecturally precise: each layer was tested independently and any one could have failed without collapsing the others. Four passed; CtpA was rejected; the respiratory arm was demoted. The scorecard on the next slide delivers those verdicts numerically. This figure makes the integration argument visually before the table confirms it.\",","+  \"speaker_notes_seed\": \"Before formal hypothesis testing began, the NB00 orientation notebook established a critical reframing. This heatmap shows the sphingolipid biosynthesis gene locus in log2(CPM+1) across all four strains: wild type (4580), the Δfur Δsspb background (4584), the intermediate strain (4659), and the fully rescued Δlpxc strain (4672). The picture is flat to slightly decreasing — not induced.\\n\\nSpeaker caveat (load-bearing): this CPM heatmap from NB00 is orientation-level and descriptive only. It does NOT license a 'ruling out' claim by itself. The formal statistical ruling-out lives in NB04, presented on slide 16: 0/6 biosynthesis genes UP at FDR<0.05; spt logFC −0.64 FDR 0.002; sphk −0.40 FDR 0.02. If an audience member asks 'does this figure prove the biosynthesis pathway isn't induced?' — the honest answer is: 'No; the CPM heatmap shows it looks flat, but slide 16 gives you the FDR-corrected numbers that license the formal claim.'\\n\\nDelivery note: 'NB00 showed us the sphingolipid pool looks flat even at this CPM-level view — biosynthesis isn't going up in the rescue strains. Slide 16 gives the formal numbers. What this pattern tells us is that the question Layer 1 must answer is about routing, not synthesis.'\\n\\nThis observation redirected the analysis: not 'why does Δfur induce sphingolipid biosynthesis?' but 'given that the CPG pool is already present in WT, what Fur-released components enable its trafficking into the outer membrane?' That question frames Layer 1 — the Fur-released TonB-dependent transporters (Path A) carry the envelope-stress fitness signal, plausibly enabling CPG routing via the shared Lpt apparatus (Uchendu 2026 bioRxiv).\\n\\nTransition: with this orientation established — Fur derepresses transport, not sphingolipid biosynthesis — we turn to the fitness data to ask which part of the Fur regulon carries phenotypic weight under envelope stress.\",","   \"evidence_anchors\": [","-    {","-      \"kind\": \"report_section\",","-      \"ref\": \"REPORT.md §Key Findings line 5\"","-    }","+    {\"kind\": \"report_section\", \"ref\": \"REPORT.md §Phase A NB00\"},","+    {\"kind\": \"report_section\", \"ref\": \"REPORT.md §Finding 4 table (sphingolipid biosynthesis constitutive; 0/6 UP; spt −0.64 FDR 0.002)\"}","   ],","   \"revision_log\": [","     {","       \"revised_at\": \"2026-06-07T00:00:00Z\",","       \"finding_id\": \"F004\",","-      \"finding_class\": \"missing_slide\",","-      \"summary\": \"Added data_figure slide at position 29 in S6 displaying figures/NB07_synthesis_master.png — the 4-panel integrative payoff promised by the throughline and named on slide 28 but absent from the deck; caption names all five adaptive layers per the fix_hint; figure is in figures_inventory.md (full authoritative inventory; omitted from the 3-figure curated shortlist but physically present on disk and REPORT-referenced at line 5).\"","+      \"finding_class\": \"claim_evidence\",","+      \"summary\": \"Caption 'ruling out Fur-driven sphingolipid biosynthesis upregulation' removed — a CPM-normalised orientation figure cannot license a rule-out claim; replaced with CPM-descriptive qualifier ('flat across strains in NB00 orientation; CPM-descriptive, not DE-tested') plus forward pointer to FDR-tested slide 16 verdict (0/6 UP; spt −0.64 FDR 0.002). Speaker notes restructured to surface the caveat as a load-bearing delivery instruction, explicitly distinguishing the NB00 orientation-level visual from the NB04 statistical evidence on slide 16.\"","     }","-  ],","-  \"added_by_revise_loop\": true","+  ]"," }"]}],"originalFile":"{\n  \"id\": null,\n  \"position\": 29,\n  \"substory_id\": \"S6\",\n  \"layout\": \"data_figure\",\n  \"content\": {\n    \"title\": \"Four-panel master figure maps all five adaptive layers onto a single envelope cross-section\",\n    \"figure\": \"figures/NB07_synthesis_master.png\",\n    \"caption\": \"Layer 1 (Fur-released transport relief), Layer 2 (ChvI two-phase cascade), Layer 3 (constitutive sphingolipid substitution), Layer 4 (PG remodeling + Pal-Tol induction), and Layer 5 (comparative route unavailability) — integrated across the *Caulobacter* Δ*lpxC* envelope. Recommended Figure 1 (REPORT.md §Key Findings; NB07_synthesis.ipynb cell 2).\",\n    \"data_source\": \"REPORT.md §Key Findings line 5; notebooks/07_synthesis.ipynb cell 2\"\n  },\n  \"speaker_notes_seed\": \"This slide exists because the throughline promised it — and slides 27 and 28 both name it explicitly — but the deck was delivering only a scorecard table in its place. The 4-panel NB07_synthesis_master.png is the integrative payoff: the one image that places all five adaptive layers into a single spatial frame of the Caulobacter outer-membrane cross-section. Walk the audience through each panel before advancing to the scorecard. Panel A and B show the envelope cross-section with the five-layer overlay: Fur-released TBDTs repositioning outer-membrane import capacity (Layer 1); ChvI temporal scheduling with early regulators and late structural genes (Layer 2); the constitutive CPG sphingolipid pool, pre-positioned in the outer leaflet by maintained Lpt machinery, occupying the space vacated by lipid A (Layer 3); downshifted PG biosynthesis with Pal-Tol specifically upregulated for retrograde phospholipid homeostasis (Layer 4). Panels C and D overlay the fitness and transcript data to show the quantitative support under each layer. The comparative Layer 5 (spt 7,0,0,0; ChvI 6,0,0,0 by NCBI) explains why this integrated program is Caulobacter-specific. The phrase 'partially independent' is architecturally precise: each layer was tested independently and any one could have failed without collapsing the others. Four passed; CtpA was rejected; the respiratory arm was demoted. The scorecard on the next slide delivers those verdicts numerically. This figure makes the integration argument visually before the table confirms it.\",\n  \"evidence_anchors\": [\n    {\n      \"kind\": \"report_section\",\n      \"ref\": \"REPORT.md §Key Findings line 5\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"revision_log\": [\n    {\n      \"revised_at\": \"2026-06-07T00:00:00Z\",\n      \"finding_id\": \"F004\",\n      \"finding_class\": \"missing_slide\",\n      \"summary\": \"Added data_figure slide at position 29 in S6 displaying figures/NB07_synthesis_master.png — the 4-panel integrative payoff promised by the throughline and named on slide 28 but absent from the deck; caption names all five adaptive layers per the fix_hint; figure is in figures_inventory.md (full authoritative inventory; omitted from the 3-figure curated shortlist but physically present on disk and REPORT-referenced at line 5).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"added_by_revise_loop\": true\n}\n","userModified":false}}
